            "title": "Safran aims to double output of engine parts at northern France facility",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>PARIS, April 13 (Reuters) - French jet engine maker Safran will invest 150 million euros ($175.31 million) in a high tonnage hydraulic press to increase the production of strategic engine parts, CEO Olivier Andries said on Monday.</p><p>\n              The 30,000-ton press, to be installed at the Gennevillers facility north of Paris by 2029, is expected to double the plant's forging capacity and will also be used to make parts for engines currently being developed for future medium-haul aircraft.</p><!-- Article --><p>\n              Castings and forgings - tough metal parts widely used in the jet engine industry - have been in short supply since the COVID-19 pandemic, contributing to delays in aircraft output. Safran says it is the only engine maker that already has its own forging capability, but that easing shortages remains one of its key challenges along with securing supplies of rare earths.</p><p>\n              Andries told analysts in February that the company would invest further in this area to reduce its dependence on a handful of outside suppliers.</p><p>\n              Safran is also increasing its military engine production and is expected to produce 108 engines in 2026, the CEO told journalists, up from 71 produced last year.</p><p>\n              ($1 = 0.8557 euros)</p><p></p><p> (Reporting by Forrest Crellin and Tim Hepher; Editing by Susan Fenton)</p><p>\n            By Forrest Crellin</p></div>",
            "link": "https://hk.marketscreener.com/news/safran-aims-to-double-output-of-engine-parts-at-northern-france-facility-ce7e50ded881f12d",
